<paragraph blockId="18.[264,1324,1634,1900]" lastBlockId="19.[264,1322,284,350]" lastPageId="19" lastPageNumber="20" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">
In the keys of 
<bibRefCitation author="Beyer" box="[440,598,1634,1660]" pageId="18" pageNumber="25" refString="Beyer, E. M. (1965) Phoridae (Diptera Brachycera). Exploration du Parc National Albert, Mission G. F. De Witte (1933 - 1935), 99, 1 - 211." type="journal article" year="1965">
Beyer (
<number box="[528,589,1634,1660]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="1965.0">1965</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
the male of this species runs to triplet 
<number box="[1069,1098,1634,1660]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="23.0">23</number>
on page 
<number box="[1212,1245,1634,1660]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="50.0">50</number>
. It fits none of the three options due to the combination of the mesopleuron having hairs and a differentiated bristle and the costal index exceeding 
<number box="[876,931,1714,1740]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="0.43">0.43</number>
. Two species running to the same triplet are the omitted: 
<taxonomicName authority="Collin" authorityName="Collin" box="[541,797,1754,1780]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="latinervis">
<emphasis box="[541,693,1754,1779]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">M. latinervis</emphasis>
(Collin)
</taxonomicName>
, which is distinguished by is conspicuously broadened vein 
<number box="[458,472,1794,1820]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="3.0">3</number>
(Rs), and the subsequently described 
<taxonomicName authority="Disney" authorityName="Disney" box="[940,1162,1794,1820]" class="Insecta" family="Phoridae" genus="Megaselia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="morani">
<emphasis box="[940,1067,1794,1819]" italics="true" pageId="18" pageNumber="19">M. morani</emphasis>
Disney
</taxonomicName>
, which has a conspicuous ventral bulge of the mid femur. It belongs to a group of subsequently described species (
<bibRefCitation author="Disney" box="[482,656,1874,1900]" pageId="18" pageNumber="25" refString="Disney, R. H. L. (2004 b) The distinctive Megaselia deltomera Schmitz 1924 (Diptera: Phoridae) belongs to a complex of sibling species. Annales Zoologici (Warszawa), 54, 687 - 6985." type="journal article" year="2004" yearSuffix="b">
Disney, 
<number box="[579,642,1874,1900]" pageId="18" pageNumber="19" value="2004.0">2004</number>
b
</bibRefCitation>
), most of which have a shorter costal index, but the same modification of the mid femur distinguishes them from the species covered by the subsequent couplets in Beyer’s key.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
